<DocsLayout title="Capability Pins" description="Capability pins: deny-based restrictions per trust tier. Floor semantics prevent privilege escalation.">
  <p>Pins define what agents cannot do. The model is deny-based: everything is allowed unless explicitly denied. Pins add restrictions. They never grant capabilities.</p>

  <img src="/diagrams/pin-enforcement.svg" alt="Pin enforcement flow: agent write → resolve trust tier → read pin.caps → merge defaults + tokens → check deny tokens → allow or silent block" class="diagram" />

  <h2>The pin model</h2>
  <p>A pin is a set of <strong>deny tokens</strong>. Each token names a capability that is blocked. An agent's effective restrictions are the union of their trust tier defaults and any explicit pins.</p>
  <p>This is <strong>floor semantics</strong>: your trust tier sets a minimum set of restrictions. Pins can raise the floor (add more restrictions) but never lower it. A T2 agent with a permissive custom pin still cannot write source code — the tier floor holds.</p>
  <pre><code># The kernel computes:
effective_denies = tier_denies | pin_denies</code></pre>

  <h2>Deny tokens</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Token</th><th>What it denies</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>write-kernel</code></td>
        <td>Writes to <code>.ostk/</code> — the OS state directory</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>modify-governance</code></td>
        <td>Writes to HUMANFILE, ENTITYFILE, GENESIS.md, AUTHORIZATION.md, Agentfile</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>write-src</code></td>
        <td>Writes to source code files</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>read-secrets</code></td>
        <td>Access to secret values via the kernel's secret mediation</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>spawn-agent</code></td>
        <td>Launching new agents from within an agent session</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>network</code></td>
        <td>Outbound network access (MCP calls, web fetches)</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Default denies per trust tier</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Tier</th><th>Identity</th><th>Default denies</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>T0</strong></td>
        <td>GPG-verified operator</td>
        <td>None. Full access.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>T1</strong></td>
        <td>Cross-signed contributor</td>
        <td><code>write-kernel</code>, <code>modify-governance</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>T2</strong></td>
        <td>Named, unverified</td>
        <td>All writes: <code>write-kernel</code>, <code>modify-governance</code>, <code>write-src</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>T3</strong></td>
        <td>Anonymous / untrusted</td>
        <td>All writes + most reads: <code>write-kernel</code>, <code>modify-governance</code>, <code>write-src</code>, <code>read-secrets</code>, <code>spawn-agent</code></td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>T0 has no restrictions by default. T3 can barely read. The floor rises as trust decreases.</p>

  <h2>Custom pins</h2>
  <p>Define custom pins under <code>.ostk/pins/&lt;name&gt;/pin.caps</code>:</p>
  <pre><code># .ostk/pins/read-only/pin.caps
read: .ostk/ .language
write:
execute: shell(readonly)
deny: write-kernel modify-governance write-src</code></pre>

  <p>Apply a pin to an agent via the <a href="/docs/agentfile">Agentfile</a>:</p>
  <pre><code>FROM auto
PROMPT "You are a code reviewer."
TOOL file:read
PIN read-only</code></pre>

  <p><code>PIN default</code> uses the tier-default pin with no additional restrictions. Omitting the PIN directive entirely has the same effect.</p>

  <h2>Floor enforcement</h2>
  <p>Pins can only add restrictions, never remove them. If a T1 agent uses a custom pin that omits <code>write-kernel</code> from its deny list, the kernel still denies <code>write-kernel</code> because the T1 tier floor includes it.</p>
  <pre><code># T1 tier floor: write-kernel, modify-governance
# Custom pin denies: write-src
# Effective: write-kernel, modify-governance, write-src
# The floor is never lowered.</code></pre>
  <p>This prevents privilege escalation through pin configuration. An operator at T1 cannot create a pin that grants T0-level access.</p>

  <h2>The deny-only trade-off</h2>
  <p>Pins are deny-only. There are no allow tokens. This is the inverse of least-privilege: everything is permitted unless explicitly denied. If you forget to add a deny token, the agent has access.</p>
  <p>This is a deliberate trade-off. Deny-only is simpler to reason about (a short list of things that are blocked) and fails open, which keeps agents productive. Allow-only (least-privilege) is safer but requires enumerating every capability an agent needs — and a missing entry blocks the agent silently, which is hard to debug. The tier floor mitigates the risk: even if your custom pin is permissive, the trust tier's default denies still apply.</p>

  <h2>Silent enforcement</h2>
  <p>When a denied operation is attempted, the kernel blocks it silently. The agent does not receive an error message — the write simply does not persist. This is intentional: agents that know about restrictions try to work around them. Agents that don't know about restrictions write normally and the OS decides what sticks.</p>
  <p>Denied operations are logged in the audit trail. The operator can review them with <code>ostk os audit</code>.</p>

  <h2>Two-layer enforcement</h2>
  <p>Pins are one of two independent enforcement layers. They complement, not replace, process-level sandboxing:</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Layer</th><th>Mechanism</th><th>What it catches</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Pins (tool layer)</strong></td>
        <td>MCP tool dispatch checks <code>pin.caps</code> before invoking tools</td>
        <td>Writes through kernel-mediated verbs (<code>file:edit</code>, <code>shell</code>). The agent calls a tool; the kernel checks the pin before the tool runs.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>nono (syscall layer)</strong></td>
        <td>Landlock (Linux) / Seatbelt (macOS) filesystem allowlist, enforced by the OS kernel</td>
        <td>Direct filesystem access. If the agent somehow bypasses tool mediation, the syscall-level sandbox catches it. Cannot be bypassed by user code.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>Enable process-level sandboxing via <code>ISOLATION nono</code> in the <a href="/docs/agentfile">Agentfile</a>. Pins and isolation enforce independently &mdash; bypassing one does not bypass the other. Together they form defense in depth: pins are the fast, fine-grained check; nono is the kernel-enforced backstop.</p>

